6/19/25, 15:38 - Mateo Cantagallo: from qiskit import QuantumCircuit, Aer, execute
from qiskit.visualization import plot_histogram

def deutsch_jozsa_oracle(n):
    """
    Placeholder oracle for 2-qubit Deutsch-Jozsa algorithm.
    Modify this to implement a specific constant or balanced function.
    """
    oracle = QuantumCircuit(n + 1)

    # Example of a balanced oracle: f(x) = x1 ‚äï x2
    oracle.cx(0, n)
    oracle.cx(1, n)

    # Example of a constant oracle (f(x) = 0): do nothing
    # Example of a constant oracle (f(x) = 1): oracle.x(n)

    return oracle

def deutsch_jozsa_algorithm(n=2):
    qc = QuantumCircuit(n + 1, n)

    # Step 1: Initialize last qubit to |1‚ü©
    qc.x(n)
    qc.h(range(n + 1))  # Step 2: Hadamard on all qubits

    # Step 3: Apply Oracle
    oracle = deutsch_jozsa_oracle(n)
    qc.append(oracle.to_gate(), range(n + 1))

    # Step 4: Hadamard on first n qubits again
    qc.h(range(n))

    # Step 5: Measure first n qubits
    qc.measure(range(n), range(n))

    return qc

if __name__ == "__main__":
    qc = deutsch_jozsa_algorithm()
    print(qc.draw())

    backend = Aer.get_backend('qasm_simulator')
    result = execute(qc, backend=backend, shots=1024).result()
    counts = result.get_counts()

    print("Result:", counts)
    plot_histogram(counts).show()
6/19/25, 15:52 - Mateo Cantagallo: from qiskit import QuantumCircuit
from qiskit_aer import Aer
from qiskit.visualization import plot_histogram

# Build your Deutsch-Jozsa circuit (e.g., using the oracle with all-zero anticontrol)
def deutsch_jozsa_circuit(n):
    qc = QuantumCircuit(n + 1, n)
    
    # Initialize output qubit to |1>
    qc.x(n)
    
    # Hadamard on all qubits
    qc.h(range(n + 1))

    # Oracle that flips output if all input qubits are |0>
    oracle = deutsch_jozsa_all_zero_anticontrol_oracle(n)
    qc.append(oracle.to_gate(), range(n + 1))

    # Hadamard on input qubits
    qc.h(range(n))

    # Measure input qubits
    qc.measure(range(n), range(n))

    return qc

# Oracle definition
def deutsch_jozsa_all_zero_anticontrol_oracle(n):
    oracle = QuantumCircuit(n + 1)
    for i in range(n):
        oracle.x(i)
    oracle.mcx(list(range(n)), n)
    for i in range(n):
        oracle.x(i)
    return oracle

# Run the simulation
if __name__ == "__main__":
    circuit = deutsch_jozsa_circuit(2)
    backend = Aer.get_backend('qasm_simulator')

    # Run the job
    job = backend.run(circuit, shots=1024)
    result = job.result()

    # Extract and display counts
    counts = result.get_counts()
    print("Result:", counts)
    plot_histogram(counts).show()
6/19/25, 15:54 - Mateo Cantagallo: from qiskit import QuantumCircuit
from qiskit_aer import Aer
from qiskit.visualization import plot_histogram
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt  # Required to display histogram

def deutsch_jozsa_all_zero_anticontrol_oracle(n):
    oracle = QuantumCircuit(n + 1)
    for i in range(n):
        oracle.x(i)  # Invert input qubits (simulate anticontrol)
    oracle.mcx(list(range(n)), n)  # Multi-controlled X on output
    for i in range(n):
        oracle.x(i)  # Undo inversion
    return oracle

def deutsch_jozsa_circuit(n):
    qc = QuantumCircuit(n + 1, n)

    qc.x(n)               # Set output qubit to |1‚ü©
    qc.h(range(n + 1))    # Apply Hadamard to all qubits

    # Apply oracle
    oracle = deutsch_jozsa_all_zero_anticontrol_oracle(n)
    qc.append(oracle.to_gate(), range(n + 1))

    qc.h(range(n))        # Apply Hadamard to input qubits
    qc.measure(range(n), range(n))  # Measure input qubits

    return qc

# Main block
if __name__ == "__main__":
    n = 2
    circuit = deutsch_jozsa_circuit(n)
    print(circuit.draw())

    backend = Aer.get_backend("qasm_simulator")
    job = backend.run(circuit, shots=1024)
    result = job.result()
    counts = result.get_counts()

    print("Measurement results:", counts)
    plot_histogram(counts)
    plt.show()

    """
